      <section name='ivan'>

         <para number='1' comment='Match for Ivan'>
         Hi, and welcome to Marina's Gift Shop. My name is Ivan and I run this store for Djentsch.
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='dmz'>
         He gets a look on his face as he starts remember his days on the DMZ in Europe and says, "You know, I remember being sent to the DMZ. Right across from where 3/11 ARC was setup in OP Romeo.
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='No match'>
         Ivan just smiles at you, and carries on arranging his dolls.
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='Marina'>
         Ivan asks, "Are you wanting to know about the planet, or the person?
         </para>

         <para number='5' comment='marina planet'>
         Ivan clears his throat and says, "The planet Marina is named after the young lady Djentsch meet while stationed in Korea. Because he wanted to learn as much about her as he could, he looked into the history of the country she is from. All locations here are named after real places in either Russia, or Korea."
         </para>

         <para number='6' comment='marina person'>
         With a twinkle in his eye, Ivan says, "Marina is the lady whom stole Djentsch's heart when he met her in Korea. She is from the small village of Khurba, Russia. A small little place that he hopes to visit one day. Marina and Djentsch were married on 28 Aug 2006."
         </para>

         <para number='7' comment='nesting dolls'>
         Ivan says, "The first Russian nesting doll (matryoshka) was born in 1890 in the workshop "Children's Education" situated in Abramtsevo estate new Moscow. Russian wooden dolls within smaller dolls were called matryoshka. In old Russian among peasants the name Matryona or Matriosha was a very popular female name. This name was associated with the image of a mother of a big peasant family who was very healthy and had a portly figure."
         </para>

         <para number='8' comment='vodka'>
         "So you want to know about Vodka do you?", asks Ivan. "Ok, in the old times Russian people didn't have any idea of getting drunk. Before the adoption of Christianity, alcoholic beverages were put on the table to celebrate thee holidays: the birth of a child, a military victory or the funeral. In acient Russia, vodka was highly appreciated and used as miracle-working medicine. Tzar Peter brought the Strict order in alcohol drinking."
         </para>

